For any tool you mention in an interview — know exactly these four things:
******************************************************************************************************************************
1. What problem does it solve?
2. How does it solve it? (one sentence mechanism)
3. What's the tradeoff vs the obvious alternative?
4. What breaks it? (the edge case / limitation)


******************************************************************************************************************************
Load Balancer:
******************************************************************************************************************************
Problem:  Single server becomes bottleneck
Mechanism: Distributes requests across server pool
vs Alternative (DNS round robin): LB is health-aware,
              DNS is blind. Use LB when you need 
              failover and session persistence.
What breaks it: LB itself becomes single point of failure
                → solution: redundant LBs (which you mentioned!)

******************************************************************************************************************************
Kafka:
******************************************************************************************************************************
Problem:  High throughput async message passing
Mechanism: Append-only log, consumers track their own offset, pub-sub architecture, publish message to topic, consumer reads
vs Alternative (RabbitMQ): Kafka retains messages after consume,
              RabbitMQ deletes. Use Kafka when multiple 
              consumers need same data or replay is needed.
What breaks it: Not designed for small fast messages 
                needing immediate response → use Redis pub/sub

******************************************************************************************************************************        
Redis:
******************************************************************************************************************************
Problem:  Database too slow for repeated reads
Mechanism: In-memory key-value store, microsecond reads
vs Alternative (Memcached): Redis supports richer data 
              structures and persistence. Use Redis when
              you need sorted sets, pub/sub, or durability.
What breaks it: Memory is expensive, can't store everything
                → cache eviction policy matters (LRU)

******************************************************************************************************************************
Database Replicas:
******************************************************************************************************************************
Problem:  Single DB can't handle read volume
Mechanism: Primary handles writes, replicas serve reads
vs Alternative (sharding): Replicas = copies of same data,
              sharding = split data. Use replicas for 
              read-heavy workload, sharding for write-heavy.
What breaks it: Replication lag → reads can be stale
                → eventual consistency tradeoff

Your hot-cold two database approach is correct for too many reads. Sharding is for too much data to fit anywhere.



1. Rate Limiting (Token Bucket)
Fixed tokens refill at constant rate
Request costs one token
No token → request rejected
Used in: Rate Limiter, API design


2. Pub/Sub Pattern
Publishers emit events to a topic
Subscribers listen to topics they care about
Decouples sender from receiver completely
Used in: Notifications, News feed, Analytics


3. Fan-out
One event → written to many places
Push fan-out: write to each follower's feed on post
Pull fan-out: follower fetches feed on login
Used in: News feed, Notifications



4. HyperLogLog
Probabilistic data structure
Counts unique items with ~1% error
Uses tiny memory vs storing every unique ID
Used in: Unique visitor counter, Analytics


5. Write-Ahead Log (WAL)
Every write logged before applying
On crash → replay log to recover
Used in: Data replication, Time series DB, KV store


6. Consistent Hashing
Nodes on a ring
Adding/removing node → only neighbor keys move
Used in: KV store, Load balancer, DB cluster


7. Consensus (Raft/Paxos) — just the concept
Multiple nodes must agree before write commits
Leader elected → coordinates writes
Used in: Distributed KV store, DB replication


8. LSM Tree vs B-Tree
LSM:    Fast writes, slower reads → time series DB
B-Tree: Fast reads, slower writes → traditional DB
Used in: Time series DB, KV store, DB cluster


9. Chunking + Checksums
Split large files into chunks
Each chunk has a checksum for integrity
Only sync changed chunks not whole file
Used in: Dropbox, Collaborative editing


10. Operational Transformation / CRDTs — just the concept
OT:    Transform conflicting edits based on position
CRDT:  Data structure that merges automatically
Both:  Resolve concurrent edits without conflict
Used in: Collaborative editing only

